		   <td><font face="verdana" size="2"><P>
 Hi,<P>

     I recently was interested in the program you use in the design of characters as well as level.  I found the correct program and wanted to
know if there was anyway to just play around with characters or zones strictly
for fun?  I have tried to open them using the proper program and everytime I
try to open various zones or what, and click in the boxes where they should appear, I get a pop-up box saying, "this program has run an illegal operation" etc, you know the one.  Let me know.  Thanks.<P>

 Allprofish

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   EverQuest's S3D files are products of in-house software technology.
It is not likely that you will find anything (besides the EverQuest program)
that can read these files at this time.  I could be wrong.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Milo Says:<BR>
<I>Yes, it is possible to ride a dragon. So far, no one has managed to
deplete the last 25% of a dragon's hit points single-handedly; this will subdue
the dragon instead of killing it, at which point the subduer can teleport to
an adjacent zone and mount the creature.</I><P>

 I wouldn't say this man. Next thing you know some 60th necro is gonna go
/pet solo Nag and your credibility will go right down the toilet. =)<P>

 Leafweir, 53rd level SK, Druzzil Ro

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   You can use a pet, just be sure that it doesn't get the last hit on
the dragon.  If it does, you won't be able to ride the dragon, and
it will never follow you unless you have a pet.  There are currently
no plans to fix this bug.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 This is in response to Stacy Griebel's statement about the sexism the female models.

 Well I too am a real female who plays EQ a lot as well.  I don't see anything sexist about the female models.  In fact I wish y'all had thrown in a bit more poly's into the bustline to make them more round and more fitting to the cleavage textures.  My only real complaint is.. as a member of the casting community... Where's *MY* cleavage?  I feel left out that I have absolutely nothing to distract the male population of Norrath unless I'm looting my corpse.  How about a nice plunging neckline with gobs of boobs hanging all over, of course the guys can have their rippling pects to display as well.  I'm sure most of them are tired of being called "sissy dress wearin casters."<P>

 Hey.. I'm all for equality of the sexes but at least make it across the board. I wanna show off my boobs too!<P>

 Venicia D'Amante

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Sweet.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Have you ever given thoughts to learning how to program? I think that with your skill at graphics. You could make nice little games with excellent graphics. Thats about it. Bye.<P>

 ps. Thanks for bearing with me on my spelling and grammer errors. I also believe in writing perfectlty. Also making many lines out of one sentence.<P>

 Bamorn Damorn

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I love programming.  It's one of my favorite things to do; I probably
like it more than creating graphics, actually.  My web site is programmed
chiefly in JavaScript (and I'll convert it to Java, once I crack the two or
three Java books sitting on the floor of my bedroom); see
<a href="http://www.milospace.net/">http://www.milospace.net/</a> and <A href="http://www.milospace.net/Boxster/">http://www.milospace.net/Boxster/</a> .
I also programmed one of the tools that many of us EverQuest personnel
use to generate a lot of the files required for the game, as well as a few
Maya scripts (Maya is a high-level 3D graphics creation package).  I've
also got countless little Windows tools that I've created for my own
personal use.<P>

   As for creating my own games, I'd likely enjoy doing that, but games
are so sophisticated nowadays that I doubt that I would ever have the
time and energy to pull it off!<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Hello Milo,<P>

     I was wondering if you knew anything about the upcoming Star Wars On Line.  In your Ask Milo column at Everlore you dont seem to be afraid to answer any question, and you dont sidetrack questions like some of the other Verant staff seem to be getting so good at. I was wondering if SWOL was going to have the ability for players to play as or become Jedi characters?  I have asked many people this question and always get the same responce, "We are not aloud to disclose any information on SWOL." Being a worshipper of Star Wars I really hope that Verant doesnt decide to take out the only reason i would ever want to play a Star Wars RPG. Jedi might be overpowering in this kind of game setting, but I will not buy the game if i can not choose to play a Jedi character.<P>

 BTW, you should try and get on the art team for SWOL, your work in EQ so far has been excellent in my opinion.  You are an excellent artist and could really help SWOL become the game it should be.<P>

 ---Han Solo wannabe

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   [I am] not [allowed] to disclose any information on SWOL.<P>

   And the Star Wars project does not need me at all.  There are
plenty of people on that team who are more than capable of
fulfilling their duties.<P>

